'''H<U+00E5>kan Eriksson''' (born January 24 1956) is a retired [[Sweden|Swedish]] ice hockey player. Eriksson began playing hockey in Bjurfors IF but was acquired by [[Skellefte<U+00E5> AIK]] in 1974. He became Swedish champions with Skellefte<U+00E5> in 1978, and was a part of Sweden's 1979 World Championship team that won bronze. During the following season he was also part of Sweden's Olympic team in the [[1980 Winter Olympics]].<ref name="SOK">{{cite web |title=H<U+00E5>kan Eriksson |url=http://www.sok.se/5.b17e0a10832cc6a9a800044029.html |work=sok.se |publisher=[[Swedish Olympic Committee]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref> After four seasons with Skellefte<U+00E5>, Eriksson moved to Stockholm and [[Djurg<U+00E5>rdens IF Hockey|Djurg<U+00E5>rdens IF]]. He won his second Swedish championship in 1983 with Djurg<U+00E5>rden. He was the team captain for two seasons, from 1982 to 1984<ref name="coach">{{cite web |url=http://difhockey.se/trojnummer.php |title=Tr<U+00F6>jnummer |accessdate=27 August 2009 |publisher=Djurg<U+00E5>rdens IF Hockey| language=Swedish }}</ref>, when he finished his career in Djurg<U+00E5>rden. During his final season in Djurg<U+00E5>rden he was again part of Sweden's Olympic team in the [[1984 Winter Olympics]].<ref name="SOK" /> He became assistant coach in the same team along with [[Lars-Fredrik Nystr<U+00F6>m]] for the rest of the 1985<U+2013>86 season when [[Gunnar Svensson]] was fired on January 21 1986.<ref name="coach" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Historia - 1980-1989 |url=http://www.difhockey.se/1980 |work=difhockey.se |publisher=[[Djurg<U+00E5>rdens IF Hockey]] |language=Swedish |accessdate=20 August 2009}}</ref> He ended his playing career in 1987 after two seasons in IFK Liding<U+00F6>.

